title: For Sale:  Mossberg 930, 3-gun, Home Defense
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Mossberg 930 waterfowl that I used for hunting, multigun and home defense. It has a 28 inches ported barrel as well as a 24 inch non-ported turkey barrel. The 24 inch barrel was special ordered from Mossberg without the ports to be legal for tactical optics class multigun and has red and green "adjustable" rifle sights. It also has a nordic component magazine tube and choate charging handle. The trigger, action, and loading port have not been touched. The 930 comes with the original magazine cap, modified choke, full choke, and turkey choke. 

The 930 has approximately 1000 rounds of birdshot. Mostly 1 ounce and 1 1/8 ounce loads. The finish on the 24 inch barrel does not have a good finish. I tried to capture the finish as best I could in the pictures. I've had no problems with the gun at all. It functions smooth and fires every time. This is the best bang for the buck to get into multigun.

No trades at this time. I hate to sell this, but I've upgraded and I need to pay for other projects. I have well over $700 in this mossberg.

title: For Sale:  Custom Mauser
postcontent:
For sale is a custom Mauser built off of a WW2 Era VZ-24. The vz. 24 rifle is a bolt-action carbine designed and produced in Czechoslovakia from 1924 to 1942. It was developed from the famous Mauser Gewehr 98 line, and features a very similar bolt design. The rifle was designed in Czechoslovakia shortly after World War I, featuring a 600 mm (23.6") barrel which was shorter and considered more handy than the 150 mm (5.9") -longer Gewehr 98. The carbine followed a similar trend in weapon design at the time, that a short rifle gave away little in ballistic efficiency at combat ranges, but was easier to handle on account of its shorter length.

The same characteristics that made the VZ -24 make this a great platform for a sporting rifle.  East to point and follow game, yet very accurate and powerful.

This rifle shoots the standard Mauser 8x57 cartridge.

The bore on this rifle is fantastic with visibly crisp rifling, and a custom target crown on the barrel for improved accuracy.  The Bishop stock is the highest quality offered with a very comfortable cheek piece. (The stock alone probably cost more than the asking price.)  This is part of a larger collection of C&R rifles I am selling.

See more photos here http://www.flickr.com/photos/18186251@N00/sets/REDACTED7093285/

This rifle is over 50 years old and can be sold face to face in Los Angeles, or shipped to a C&R holder.  Face to Face cash sale preferred.  No trades and price is firm.

title: For Sale:  Walther P99 9mm QPQ w/ night sights
postcontent:
**I've reduced my asking price from $700 to $625.**

This is a pistol that you're not likely to come across again, especially one in this condition. This is a 1st generation Walther P99 9mm with Meprolight night sights. It is 100% German manufactured and proofmarked, was imported by Interarms, and has a date code on the frame of "KI", which is 1998 manufacture. The slide has a factory finish called "QPQ", which stands for "Quench/Polish/Quench". It is basically a hard, highly corrosion-resistant Tenifer finish (similar to Glock) that is not phosphated over, which gives it an appearance similar to a matte-finish hard chrome. Not many Walthers were made with this finish and if you do some research, you'll see that it's quite desirable among Walther enthusiasts. I purchased this pistol secondhand in 2005, added the night sights, and function-tested it with a couple hundred rounds of various FMJ and hollowpoints. It was extremely accurate and 100% reliable, just as all of my other P99 pistols were. I thoroughly cleaned the pistol, lubed it, and stored it. As you can see, it is in exceptional condition and is very close to new. The pistol comes with (2) 16rd factory mags, the original case, factory test target, original sights, extra back straps, and owner's manual. FYI, the 16rd Walther P99 mags are very difficult to find and were what the pistol was originally designed for...however at some point and for some reason, Walther changed the standard mags to 15rds.  I have some additional 16rd Walther factory mags in like-new condition that I can sell with the pistol for $40 each. 

I can text or email additional high-quality photos if you're interested. Just let me know.

title: For Sale:  Remington 870 Police Magnum - NOT an Express!
postcontent:
This is NOT a Remington Express gun - this is Police Magnum, which is much more durable!

Remington Police Magnums come with a parkerized finish on an 18" barrel (as opposed to a Blued finish on an Express); feature a stronger sear spring and magazine spring; better extractor and ejector, and much more.

Shotgun has rifle sights and has been gone over completely by in-house Remington LE Certified Armorer. This shotgun goes for $650 new in the box if your are Law Enforcement.

While the 870 Express is still an 870, the best pump shotgun on the market, there are some very important cosmetic and functional differences between it and the 870 Police. To our customers in Law Enforcement, Military, Corrections, and Security, whose lives depend upon the unfailing performance of Remington shotguns, the Police modifications are of paramount importance.

Synopses of the variances are provided below.
870 Police shotguns go thru a special 23 station check list – ranging from visual inspection, functional testing, test firing, and final inspection.
All Police shotguns are assembled in a “special build area” at the plant in Ilion, NY. This section is secured and serves only to build LE and Military shotguns, with the same factory personnel working at that assignment each shift.
All parts that enter the “special build area” are visually inspected by hand to ensure top quality and functionality.
Due to heavy recoil in buck and slug loads, all 870 Police guns have a longer magazine spring which ensures positive feed and function.
A heavier sear spring is used to generate a reliable, positive trigger pull between 5 and 8 lbs.
A heavier carrier dog spring is used to ensure when the carrier elevates the shell, it will be held there until the bolt can push it into the chamber. This ensures positive feeding when using heavier payload rounds.
Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety.
The fore-end on the Express model is longer and not compatible with many police shotgun vehicle racks. The Police shotguns utilize the heavy duty Remington Stocks and Fore-ends.
The Express model will not allow for the addition of an extension tube without physical modification to the tube and barrel, which can nullify the warranty.
The Express model has a Bead Blast Bluing finish while the Police models utilize Parkerization. The Express model utilizes a synthetic trigger housing while the Police models use a compressed metal housing.
The Police shotgun barrel is locked down with a “ball detent” system in conjunction with the magazine cap vs. a lesser grade “synthetic magazine spring retainer” lock down as used on the Express system.
The receivers used in Police guns are “vibra honed” to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization.
Police shotguns use machined ejectors and extractors, as opposed to powdered metal cast which are utilized on the Express models.


$500.
Not interested in trades.
Requires FFL transfer.
